</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="19BC6515FFB4B041FF73FF30407CFE2D" pageId="1" pageNumber="270" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="5119369EFFB4B041FF73FF30407CFE2D" blockId="1.[151,1436,152,431]" pageId="1" pageNumber="270">
<emphasis id="63D2EA8CFFB4B041FF73FF304559FF4D" bold="true" box="[199,312,184,207]" pageId="1" pageNumber="270">Remarks:</emphasis>
The present specimens agree with the original descriptions and keys by Alcock (1901) and 
<bibRefCitation id="35374B6FFFB4B041FABAFF3041F9FF4D" box="[1294,1432,184,207]" pageId="1" pageNumber="270" refId="ref1851" refString="Chan, T. Y. (1996) Crustacea Decapoda Crangonidae: Revision of the three closely related genera Aegaeon Agassiz, 1846, Pontocaris Bate, 1888 and Parapontocaris Alcock, 1901. In: Crosnier, A. (Ed.), Resultats des Campagnes MUSORSTOM 15. Memoires du Museum national d'Histoire naturelle, Serie A, Zoologie, 168, 269 ̶ 336." type="journal article">Chan (1996)</bibRefCitation>
. Even though, the tubercles on the dorsal side of abdomen III are not round, but only appear as a small dot. Few 
<taxonomicName id="96A64D1DFFB4B041FA8BFF5044BBFE8D" authority="affinis" authorityName="affinis (Alcock" authorityYear="1901" class="Malacostraca" family="Crangonidae" genus="Pontocaris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="270" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="affinis" subSpecies="affinis">
<emphasis id="63D2EA8CFFB4B041FA8BFF5044BBFE8D" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="270">P. affinis affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
individuals were noticed during September to December among the deep sea landings which included 
<taxonomicName id="96A64D1DFFB4B041FF23FE904548FEAD" box="[151,297,280,303]" class="Malacostraca" family="Pandalidae" genus="Heterocarpus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="270" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="63D2EA8CFFB4B041FF23FE904548FEAD" box="[151,297,280,303]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="270">Heterocarpus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
sp. The fecundity was observed as 400- 
<specimenCount id="47A0FD17FFB4B041FD5CFE90472AFEAD" box="[744,843,280,303]" pageId="1" pageNumber="270" type="egg">500 eggs</specimenCount>
per female (egg size range: 
<quantity id="965E9B7BFFB4B041FB3FFE904173FEAD" box="[1163,1298,280,303]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="5.0" pageId="1" pageNumber="270" unit="mm" value="0.55" valueMax="0.6" valueMin="0.5">0.5–0.6 mm</quantity>
), which was comparatively lesser than to any other caridean shrimp. Previously, this species was recorded from various locations along the Indian coast (
<collectingCountry id="29B1760EFFB4B041FE22FED04592FEED" box="[406,499,344,367]" name="India" pageId="1" pageNumber="270">Bombay</collectingCountry>
, &amp; Bay of Bengal) and 
<collectingCountry id="29B1760EFFB4B041FD4DFED0471BFEED" box="[761,890,344,367]" name="Madagascar" pageId="1" pageNumber="270">Madagascar</collectingCountry>
at depths of 
<quantity id="965E9B7BFFB4B041FBBEFED04017FEED" box="[1034,1142,344,367]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.04" metricValueMax="1.75" metricValueMin="0.32999999999999996" pageId="1" pageNumber="270" unit="m" value="104.0" valueMax="175.0" valueMin="33.0">33–175 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation id="35374B6FFFB4B041FB32FED041F7FEED" box="[1158,1430,344,367]" pageId="1" pageNumber="270" refId="ref2143" refString="Sankolli, K. N. &amp; Shenoy, S. (1979) Laboratory behaviour of a crangonid shrimp Pontocaris pennata Bate and its three larval stages. Journal of marine Biological Association of India, 18, 62 ̶ 70." type="journal article">Sankolli &amp; Shenoy 1979</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="35374B6FFFB4B041FF23FEF04575FE0D" box="[151,276,376,399]" pageId="1" pageNumber="270" refId="ref1851" refString="Chan, T. Y. (1996) Crustacea Decapoda Crangonidae: Revision of the three closely related genera Aegaeon Agassiz, 1846, Pontocaris Bate, 1888 and Parapontocaris Alcock, 1901. In: Crosnier, A. (Ed.), Resultats des Campagnes MUSORSTOM 15. Memoires du Museum national d'Histoire naturelle, Serie A, Zoologie, 168, 269 ̶ 336." type="journal article">Chan 1996</bibRefCitation>
; Radhakrishnan 
<emphasis id="63D2EA8CFFB4B041FE7AFEF04668FE0D" box="[462,521,375,399]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="270">et al.</emphasis>
2011). But, in the present study it is obtained from Quilon bank at 
<quantity id="965E9B7BFFB4B041FAA3FEF041F6FE0D" box="[1303,1431,376,399]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.75" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.5" pageId="1" pageNumber="270" unit="m" value="275.0" valueMax="300.0" valueMin="250.0">250–300 m</quantity>
, indicating that 
<taxonomicName id="96A64D1DFFB4B041FE83FE1045BCFE2D" authority="affinis" authorityName="affinis (Alcock" authorityYear="1901" box="[311,477,407,431]" class="Malacostraca" family="Crangonidae" genus="Pontocaris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Decapoda" pageId="1" pageNumber="270" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="affinis" subSpecies="affinis">
<emphasis id="63D2EA8CFFB4B041FE83FE1045BCFE2D" box="[311,477,407,431]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="270">P. affinis affinis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has a wide depth distribution along the Indian Ocean.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
